body:
I'm really curious why/how #17093 passes the build if all of these are failing. I'll try bisecting from the c95aa9950 build using this code:

```
#![feature(unboxed_closures, unboxed_closure_sugar)]

fn bug() {
  let c = box |&:| {};
}
```

(both this and the OP's code compile on c95aa9950, for reference)

This is falling through a [wildcard match clause in `debug_info.rs`](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/aef6c4b1382dcf2f943bd5872656625f935c0b7c/src/librustc/middle/trans/debuginfo.rs#L513):

```
        match ty::get(type_).sty {
            ty::ty_nil      |
            ty::ty_bot      |
            ty::ty_bool     |
(...snipped...)
            _ => {
                cx.sess().bug(format!("get_unique_type_id_of_type() - unexpected type: {}, {:?}",
                                      ppaux::ty_to_string(cx.tcx(), type_).as_slice(),
                                      ty::get(type_).sty).as_slice())
            }
        };
```

This is probably a relatively easy fix—it's generating some sort of unique representation for each type.

@emk you can see my attempt at fixing that here
https://github.com/nathantypanski/rust/commit/8861e1d7fda3fd4cbb2de0a80e29c36d4ebc1573

It didn't work, for reasons that are unknown to me. But, hey, it adds to that pattern match like you suggest.
